Introduction

The 2018 FIFA World Cup, which was held in Russia, was one of the most anticipated events in the sports world, with millions of fans around the globe sharing their thoughts and emotions on social media platforms such as Twitter. By using text mining techniques, we aim to analyze the tweets dataset, by identifying the most common tweets topics, and grouping them into clusters. The aim of this project is to provide valuable insights into the social media landscape surrounding the 2018 World Cup, and how fans engaged with the tournament.

2. Data

For this task, we have chosen the FIFA World Cup 2018 Tweets dataset from kaggle (source https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/rgupta09/world-cup-2018-tweets), which consists of approximately 530 000 tweets from 2018 Football World Cup. The tweets were gathered between start of Round of 16, and Final. The dataset was already pre-processed, including removing users, websites, hashtags, mentions, special characters or retweet information from tweets body. Duplicates were removed and some of the shortenings, like nt, ll etc. were replaced with their proper full-word form.

In our analysis, we have started with randomly selecting just 5% of the whole dataset, removed stopwords, uppercase letters, punctuation and numbers, resulting with following graph of top words.

Plotting results for 30 most frequent words and wordcloud of those words:

As the France football team won the 2018 FIFA World Cup, it is not a surprise, that the word France will be placed at the top of the comparison alongside with words such as world, final, or cup. Going further, we can spot names of the particular countries, as Croatia (finalist) England and Belgium (semi finalists), or Russia (host). Interestingly, the word racism and xenophobi appeared in top 30 words.

3. Modeling

In order to achieve our goals within this project, we will use two common text mining techniques. First one will be to cluster using hierarchical clustering with Wards method, and K-means algorithm. When it comes to topic modeling, the Latent Dirichlet Allocation was performed. Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) is a generative probabilistic model for collections of discrete data, such as text corpora. It assumes that each document in a corpus is a mixture of latent topics, and each topic is characterized by a distribution over words. LDA aims to find the underlying topics in a corpus of documents by estimating the topic distributions and word distributions. The main idea behind LDA is that it tries to discover the hidden topics in the text data by observing the word frequencies in the documents and constructing a probability distribution over topics for each document. LDA is widely used in natural language processing and information retrieval for tasks such as topic modeling, document classification, and clustering.

4. Evaluation (quality of obtained results)

We have started with clustering the tweets with hierarchical clustering and K-means.

##   cluster size                                          top_words

## 2       2   54          golden, golden_ball, ball, mbappe, kylian
## 3       3   34 finals, quarter, quarter_finals, semi, semi_finals
## 4       4   15           power, exo, power_power, power_exo, play
## 5       5   30       home, coming, coming_home, brought, football

Summarizing main discoveries from our clustering algorithms approach we have found that having clustered into 5 clusters the outcome is as follows: The biggest cluster (1394) which contains following top words: france, final, croatia, finals, quarter and those words regards the final of the World Cup 2018 Next cluster, which has a size of 45, contains following top words: golden, golden_ball, luka, modric, ball which describes the matter of Luka Modric being given a Golden Ball award. The smallest cluster (13) has such a top words: fake_love, fake, love, play, play_fake Our final proposal for 2-dimensional representation was explaining the 3.65% of the whole tweets variability.

Lets move to the LDA method. Following parameters were considered:

  • Alpha document-topic density; the higher alpha is, documents are made of more topics
  • Beta topic-word density; the higher beta is, topics are made of more words in the corpus
  • Number of topics to be extracted from the corpus
  • Number of topic terms composed in a single topic

With the use ob basic LDA algorithm, we can see main topics and tags within the topics across all tweets.

Chart above represents most commonly used words for three topics. As we can see, in this part of analysis we still do include the stop words, so in next step, we will exclude those and stem the words to their basic form.

As we can see, both of the topics look pretty similar, with franc as the mainly used word. From the top words, we can conclude, that first topic was more focused on emotional aspect, mentioning players, congratulations, while second one was more informational, with teams perspective, and goals information.

5. Summary

Given such a huge data set (530 000 tweets), it is essential to somehow find underlying patterns and stack or combine similarly behaving information into more common groups. Therefore we have used the hierarchical clustering algorithm, which bases on the similarity distance metrics, to overcome the problem of huge data sets inference. After performing the clustering algorithms, we have performed the analysis of the main topics, and proposed the 2-dimensional representations of the clustered tweets. Further on, with the use of LDA text mining method, we have modeled main topics with regard to tweets from World Cup 2018. Initially dataset consisted of 530 000 tweets which was much too much, therefore we sampled randomly 5% of the tweets which result in 26 500 tweets in total to the analysis.
